  "signature": "ed25519:b2d4f6a8c0e2b4d6f8a0c2e4b6d8f0a2c4e6b8d0f2a4c6e8b0d2f4a6c8e0b2d4",
  "hasCredibilityFactor": [
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Software quality assurance",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "FEA solver and pre/post-processing software must be under documented version control with traceable release notes; all scripts used in the analysis pipeline are archived in the project repository with hash verification.",
      "rationale": "Ansys Mechanical 2022 R2 and custom Python post-processing scripts are managed under Git version control (tag v2.3.1). Software qualification records on file confirm installation verification and operational qualification for the solver version used. Achieved Gradation 3 exceeds the required Gradation 2 for a Medium model-risk application."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Numerical code verification",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Solver must pass standard benchmark problems (NAFEMS LE1, LE10) with error less than 1% relative to analytical solutions; patch-test compliance documented.",
      "rationale": "Ansys Mechanical 2022 R2 has been verified against NAFEMS linear elastic benchmark suite LE1 and LE10. Results show <0.4% deviation from analytical solutions. Patch-test compliance confirmed in solver documentation. Required and achieved levels both at Gradation 2, consistent with medium-risk classification."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Discretization error",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "A systematic mesh convergence study must demonstrate that QoI (stiffness, yield force, force at 40 mm) change by less than 2% between the penultimate and final refinement levels; Richardson extrapolation applied where applicable.",
      "rationale": "Four-level mesh refinement study performed on the pedicle screw-rod construct. QoI variation between mesh levels 3 and 4 was 0.8% for stiffness, 1.1% for yield force, and 0.9% for force at 40 mm. Richardson extrapolation applied; grid convergence index (GCI) < 1.5% for all QoI. Achieved Gradation 3 exceeds required Gradation 2."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Numerical solver error",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Iterative solver residuals must converge below 1e-6 for all load steps; energy balance error must remain below 0.1% throughout the nonlinear solution sequence.",
      "rationale": "Nonlinear quasi-static analyses employed Newton-Raphson iteration with force residual tolerance 1e-7. Energy balance errors remained below 0.05% across all 11 specimen simulations. No unconverged load steps observed. Required and achieved levels both at Gradation 2."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Use error",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "rationale": "Model setup, boundary condition application, and post-processing were performed by a senior biomechanical engineer with 8 years of FEA experience and independently reviewed by a second qualified analyst. A documented simulation plan (SP-001) was followed; all deviations recorded and adjudicated. The structured acceptance criteria level for use-error control is consistent with medium model influence and medium decision consequence, where independent review and a documented simulation plan constitute adequate assurance at Gradation 2. No structured acceptanceCriteria field is recorded for this factor because the project quality plan (QP-2024-003) captures the procedural requirements by reference and the team judged that inline documentation was unnecessary given the low residual risk at this gradation level."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Model form",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Model form selection must be justified by published literature or prior validation studies; all simplifying assumptions (contact formulation, material constitutive law, geometric idealizations) must be explicitly documented and their impact on QoI bounded by sensitivity analysis.",
      "rationale": "Linear elastic titanium alloy (Ti-6Al-4V, E=114 GPa, ν=0.34) with frictional contact (μ=0.3, augmented Lagrange) used for screw-rod and screw-vertebral body interfaces. Geometric fidelity maintained from manufacturer CAD files. Sensitivity analysis showed ±10% variation in friction coefficient produced <3% change in yield force. Model form consistent with published FDA guidance and prior ASTM F1717 FEA literature. Required and achieved levels both at Gradation 3."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Model inputs",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Material properties must be sourced from peer-reviewed literature or direct coupon testing; geometric inputs must be traceable to calibrated CMM measurements or manufacturer-certified drawings; uncertainty in key inputs must be quantified and propagated to QoI.",
      "rationale": "Ti-6Al-4V material properties sourced from MMPDS-12 and confirmed by manufacturer certification. UHMWPE block properties (E=0.93 GPa) from published compression testing data (Kurtz 2009). Geometric inputs derived from manufacturer-certified CAD drawings (tolerance ±0.02 mm). Monte Carlo uncertainty propagation (n=1000) performed on elastic modulus and friction coefficient; 95th-percentile QoI uncertainty <4%. Required and achieved levels both at Gradation 3."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Test samples",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Validation dataset must include N≥10 physical specimens from at least two independent laboratories; specimen traceability (lot numbers, dimensional inspection records) must be documented; inter-laboratory variability must be characterized.",
      "rationale": "N=11 non-cannulated 7.5 mm pedicle screw constructs tested across two independent laboratories (FDA CDRH OSEL and DePuy Synthes internal test facility). All specimens traced to production lot certificates with dimensional inspection records confirming conformance to design drawings. Inter-laboratory coefficient of variation for stiffness was 4.2%, for yield force 5.1%, within acceptable bounds. Required and achieved levels both at Gradation 3."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Test conditions",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Test conditions must span the range of clinically relevant loading scenarios; at minimum, two independent load configurations or load magnitudes must be evaluated to characterize model behavior across the COU envelope.",
      "rationale": "Testing was performed under a single ASTM F1717 compression-bending configuration (5° offset, 10 mm anterior load application). While this configuration is the regulatory standard for pedicle screw constructs, only one test condition was evaluated. The achieved Gradation 2 falls below the required Gradation 3 because the COU envelope includes varied surgical implantation angles (5°–15°) not covered by the single test condition. This shortfall is acknowledged and partially mitigated by the conservative nature of the standard F1717 configuration, which represents a bounding case for most clinical loading scenarios."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Equivalency of input parameters",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "All model input parameters must be demonstrably equivalent to the physical test conditions; any discrepancies in boundary conditions, loading rates, or fixture compliance must be quantified and shown to produce less than 5% change in QoI.",
      "rationale": "Boundary conditions in the FEA model replicate the ASTM F1717 fixture geometry, including UHMWPE block dimensions, pin diameter, and load application point, directly from test fixture drawings. Load application rate equivalency confirmed (quasi-static, 5 mm/min test vs. quasi-static FEA). Fixture compliance measured experimentally (0.12 mm/kN) and incorporated into the model as a linear spring element. Sensitivity analysis showed fixture compliance representation affected stiffness QoI by 1.8%. Required and achieved levels both at Gradation 3."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Output comparison",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Quantitative comparison metric must account for experimental uncertainty; E/uval ratio must be below 1.96 for all primary QoI; percent difference between FEA prediction and experimental mean must be below 10% for all QoI.",
      "rationale": "Validation metric E/uval computed for stiffness (0.84), yield force (1.21), and force at 40 mm (1.07), all below the 1.96 threshold. Percent differences: stiffness 3.2%, yield force 6.8%, force at 40 mm 4.1%, all below 10%. Combined measurement uncertainty (uval) estimated from inter-laboratory variability and load cell calibration uncertainty (k=2). Required and achieved levels both at Gradation 3."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Relevance of the quantities of interest",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "QoI selected for validation must be directly linked to the clinical or regulatory decision; the mapping from QoI to device performance claims must be explicitly documented in the simulation plan.",
      "rationale": "Three QoI selected — construct stiffness, yield force, and force at 40 mm displacement — directly correspond to the ASTM F1717 regulatory acceptance criteria and the device performance claims in the 510(k) submission. Stiffness is a primary indicator of construct rigidity; yield force and force at 40 mm characterize structural integrity under worst-case loading. QoI-to-claim mapping documented in Simulation Plan SP-001 Section 4.2. Required and achieved levels both at Gradation 3."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Relevance of the validation activities to the COU",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Validation activities must use the same device geometry, material lot, and loading configuration as the intended COU; any differences between the validation context and the COU must be documented and their impact on model credibility assessed.",
      "rationale": "Validation specimens are production-representative non-cannulated 7.5 mm pedicle screws from the same design family as the COU device. ASTM F1717 test configuration matches the regulatory submission context. Differences between validation and COU (single test condition vs. range of clinical implantation angles) are documented and addressed under the Test conditions factor. The validation activity is assessed as directly relevant to the COU at Gradation 3. Required and achieved levels both at Gradation 3."
    }
  ],
  "hasWeakener": [],
  "hasDecisionRecord": {
    "id": "https://uofa.net/synth/decision/nagaraja-cou1-decision-001",
    "type": "DecisionRecord",
    "actor": "https://uofa.net/synth/actor/fda-cdrh-osel-credibility-team",
    "role": "Credibility assessment team",
    "outcome": "Accepted",
    "rationale": "Overall credibility assessment yields an Accepted decision. Twelve of thirteen V&V 40 factors meet or exceed their required gradation levels. The single shortfall — Test conditions at Gradation 2 against a required Gradation 3 — is mitigated by the conservative bounding nature of the ASTM F1717 single-configuration test and the robust quantitative validation results (all E/uval < 1.96, all QoI differences < 10%). The model is judged sufficiently credible for its intended use in supporting the 510(k) submission for the non-cannulated 7.5 mm pedicle screw construct.",
    "decidedAt": "2026-04-19T00:00:00Z"
  },
